    <!-- INTRO -->
    <p>I'm 64. For most of my adult life I treated sleep like a negotiable — something to compress when work or life got busy, and catch up on when things slowed down. I was active, ate reasonably well, stayed in decent shape. Sleep felt like a background variable, not a performance lever.</p>

    <p>It wasn't until I started paying close attention to how my body was actually recovering — or not recovering — that the picture shifted. I'd be hitting my protein, working out regularly, doing most things right. But the recovery felt slower than it should. The soreness lasted longer. The strength gains stalled. And the muscle I was working to hold onto seemed to slip anyway.</p>

    <p>The missing variable wasn't effort. It wasn't protein. <strong>It was the repair window I was shortchanging every night.</strong></p>

    <p>Sleep is when muscle gets rebuilt. Not during the workout — the workout is the stimulus. The actual repair, the actual synthesis, the actual growth happens while you're asleep. And when that window is consistently cut short or disrupted, you're not just tired the next day. You're actively working against the muscle maintenance you're trying to protect.</p>

